  "text": "Insulin resistance. Insulin resistance is a common feature of NAFLD that contributes to its pathogenesis [CITATION_1] . Insulin resistance is characterized by reduced glucose disposal in nonhepatic tissues, including adipose tissue and muscle [CITATION_2] . Insulin resistance in adipose tissue leads to inappropriate release of fatty acids through dysregulated lipolysis that further contributes to impaired insulin signaling throughout the body. Studies have shown metabolic crosstalk between adipose tissue and the liver. Adiponectin, IL-6 and ",
